<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 93 / UK Company News: Institutions bid for 2bn BT shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSTITUTIONAL shareholders had bid for more than 2bn British
Telecommunications shares after the international offer closed yesterday.
The final figures will not be released until tomorrow, but SG Warburg and
Co, global coordinators of the bookbuilding exercise, said that orders for
2bn shares had been received by the close of the first day of bidding and
that the book had grown since then.
A total of 1.2bn shares are on sale, tentatively split equally between
institutions and retail investors although the ratio might be changed over
the weekend. Trading in the partly paid shares begins on Monday.
Of the institutional bids received it is believed that as many as 1.5bn were
at a price equivalent to about 12p over yesterday's closing price of 408p
for existing shares. The premium is close to the theoretical value to
investors of 13p a share of buying part-paid shares.
As a result of the demand, several leading UK institutional investors said
that they expected the deal to be highly successful but they no longer
thought the shares worth bidding for at this price.
'It's just not worth it at this level,' said one life insurance company
investment manager.
Another insurance company fund manager said that while he had placed bids
for up to 1m shares, he realised that the prices he offered for them were
too low relative to where BT shares were trading late Friday.
'We won't get any shares and we don't care to at these prices', he said.
Figures from the first day's bidding suggest that UK institutions are less
enthusiastic than their counterparts abroad about the new shares. Although
UK shareholders account for well over half of all current BT investors, they
were only half of all bidders on the first day.
Retail investors have applied for just over 1bn BT shares in the UK public
offer, according to final figures released yesterday. This is slightly more
than expected but well down on applications for 1.7bn in the last sale of
government BT shares in 1991.
</TEXT>
