<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 93 / Parsons shows off first aero-engine fan case for Rolls-Royce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TREVOR MURCH, managing director of Parsons, the Newcastle upon Tyne
turbine generator plant, yesterday showed off the company's first
aero-engine fan case for Rolls-Royce Aerospace Group, Chris Tighe writes.
The Pounds 250,000 case, produced for the Rolls-Royce BR211-535E4, is part
of the company's move into new product areas. It is the first large
Rolls-Royce component to be made by Northern Engineering Industries,
Parsons' parent company, since NEI was taken over by Rolls-Royce four years
ago.
Parsons, part of Rolls-Royce Industrial Power Group, won the 10-year
contract against stiff competition from within and outside the company. It
has become one of two fan-case production sites within Rolls-Royce.
The fan cases are made of titanium, aluminium and Kevlar, a synthetic fibre
also used in bullet-proof vests. They are being produced in a former
pipemaking building, refurbished at a cost of Pounds 6m. Production of the
cases, which each need 800 worker hours, should reach one a fortnight this
year and eventually output is expected to rise to two a week, generating
annual turnover of Pounds 25m for Parsons.
The BR211-535 is one of Rolls-Royce's most successful aero-engines, used by
more than 80 per cent of Boeing 757 operators.
</TEXT>
