<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 93 / New Nigerian election date set
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S military government will hold new presidential elections on August
14, but only one party is prepared to take part.
The decision comes four days after President Ibrahim Babangida withdrew his
offer to the parties to form an unelected interim government when he hands
over power on August 27.
Last week's mass protests in Lagos and other mainly Yoruba cities showed
such hostility to any new elections that campaigning or polling in the
south-west of Nigeria could be impractical.
The Social Democratic party (SDP) last week declared a boycott of fresh
polls under President Babangida, saying they would have no credibility. The
SDP's candidate, Mr Moshood Abiola, had a clear lead in the elections in
June when the government suspended the release of the results.
The National Republican Convention (NRC) said last night the party was ready
for elections and would decide on Wednesday how to choose their candidate.
According to the SDP and the protesters who turned out in Lagos and other
parts of the south-west last week, there is no need for a re-run. Most
voters, politicians and official foreign observers judged the June 12 polls
to be well-run and relatively fair.
The government annulled the polls because, it alleged, one or both of the
candidates had made 'negative use of money' during the campaigning and had
personal or business interests at odds with the office of head of state.
The government secretly organised a series of lawsuits after the elections
so the army could keep power, a top official with the organisation that
filed the suits said yesterday, AP reports.
Mr Abimola Davis of the Association for Better Nigeria said the annulment of
the elections was 'an organised confusion by just a few of us to prolong the
lifespan of the present military administration'. The association filed
lawsuits claiming the two candidates seeking the presidency were corrupt and
the president should remain in power. Mr Davis signed each of the suits.
</TEXT>
