<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 93 / Attali quits after damning report: EBRD president will
'waive termination allowance'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JACQUES ATTALI yesterday resigned as president of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, two months earlier than expected and only
hours after the completion of an official report highly critical of his
extravagant expenditure and management style.
In an emotive resignation letter, presented to an EBRD board meeting
yesterday morning, Mr Attali said he would 'waive the termination allowance
(of more than Pounds 147,000 tax-free) to which I am entitled under my
employment contract'. He said that the interests of the bank 'are now best
served if I leave my pos-ition as president immediately'. The board was also
shown the draft reply from Mrs Anne Wibble, Swedish finance minister and
chairman of the bank's governors. In it, she offered to waive any claims the
bank might have on him arising from its audit committee's inquiry into his
conduct and the bank's expenditure.
The terms of both letters need approval by the bank's governors, most of
whom are finance ministers, before the resignation takes formal effect. Not
all the governors support giving Mr Attali immunity against future claims
against him by the bank.
The audit committee has been working on its report since May 10, after the
Financial Times disclosed that the bank had spent Pounds 200m on fitting out
its new headquarters and other expenses, more than twice the amount it had
lent or invested in eastern Europe and the countries of the former Soviet
Union, whose economies it was set up to help.
The report is filled with what Mrs Wibble described yesterday as 'serious'
criticisms of Mr Attali. It highlights the Pounds 1.4m spent by the bank on
flights in private jets on 57 occasions. Of these flights, 48 were arranged
with a French-based company, Air Entreprise, and most were authorised by Mr
Attali's office.
The audit committee said: 'The Bank's frequent use of chartered aircraft for
travel to destinations well served by scheduled airlines is inappropriate
given its status as a publicly funded development institution.'
It continues: 'The selection of Air Entreprise as provider of most of the
charter flights taken before January 1993 did not result from a competitive
tendering process and was in nearly every case more expensive than other
charter airlines. This represents a regrettable deviation from acceptable
practice for a public sector institution.'
Mr Attali reimbursed the bank with a cheque for Pounds 41,377 relating to
seven flights in private jets in early 1992. His staff told the committee
that Mr Attali signed the cheque on or about February 10 1993, but it was
mislaid. The report said: 'The cheque was paid into the EBRD bank account on
May 4 1993, ie, after the start of the present inquiry.'
Despite several requests, it continued, the committee had not been provided
with 'adequate' evidence to establish whether these flights were wholly for
private purposes and whether the Pounds 41,377 cheque was genuinely mislaid
or whether it was drawn at a later date than February 10.
The report also attacked Mr Attali for taking possession of three different
company cars within a 10-week period beginning in March 1991. 'The large
number of cars used by the president in rapid succession creates an
impression of extravagance which is inappropriate for the head of a
development institution', it said.
Mr Attali was also criticised for having charged 'significant amounts of
expenditure of a private nature, or for which no supporting invoices have
been provided' to the bank on his corporate credit card in 1992 and 1993.
The report notes that it was 'only on June 22 1993, ie, since the start of
the present inquiry, that the president reimbursed expenses totalling Pounds
30,431 which had been incurred during 1992 and 1993'. It also said that fees
received by Mr Attali for making speeches 'appear to be inconsistent with
the Code of Conduct of the Bank'. Mr Attali had a contract with Asahi
Shimbun, a Japanese newspaper, which paid him Dollars 20,000 a year for two
years plus Dollars 30,000 for making a speech in the spring of last year.
Mr Attali's responsibilities have been taken temporarily by Mr Ron Freeman,
first vice-president, pending the appointment of a permanent successor.
Weighty dossier, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
