<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major hails new indications of
'recovery'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN was coming out of recession and leading Europe into recovery, Mr
John Major, the prime minister, told the Commons yesterday.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, was also in buoyant mood when, while
stressing that the content of his November Budget had yet to be decided, he
sought to reassure Tory backbenchers alarmed by the possibility of increases
in income tax.
Both the prime minister and the chancellor emphasised the significance of
the continuing fall in unemployment, coupled with the lowest rate of
inflation for nearly 30 years.
Mr Major commented: 'Taken with the remarkable figures on Tuesday on
manufacturing output, I think we can now say with some certainty that there
is clear evidence of a recovery gathering pace.'
Reaffirming his determination to reduce the Pounds 50bn public sector
borrowing requirement, the chancellor said he shared the instincts of the
rightwing Tory MPs in the 92 Group that public expenditure restraints should
be the first consideration.
Mr Clarke described as 'slight' the additional revenue which would be raised
by increasing the 40p rate, and recalled that higher yields had resulted
from the cuts made in the 'extraordinary high levels' of taxation imposed by
the last Labour government.
He accused Labour MPs of always wanting to put up taxation 'on somebody or
other', while, as a Conservative chancellor, he was being reminded by
backbench colleagues of their party's commitment to continue to reduce
income tax 'when it is prudent to do so'.
Sir Peter Tapsell (C Lindsey East) said estimates like those which had
produced the figure of Pounds 50bn were notoriously unreliable.
Mr Clarke answered that he had 'never drunk of the pure milk of monetarism'.
But the PSBR did constitute a serious problem and the monthly figures were
running in line with the forecast, adding: 'If the PSBR falls faster than I
am expecting I can probably deal with any problems that may cause with
considerable ease.'
</TEXT>
