<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (25): 'Without
Lloyd's, all this would have gone' - Despite recent losses, a Scottish
landowner will continue to be a Name, as he struggles to keep up his family
home / Serious Riches
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHERE THE river Girvan bends along the three-mile drive up to Blairquhan
castle in the Scottish Lowlands, you catch the first glimpse of the stone
Tudor mansion on its fern-green perch.
Sheep graze at the foot of the castle's drawing room, and, from inside the
calm of its Thai silk-covered walls, you watch the Girvan winding its way
between the gentle hills and into the woods.
The beauty is not entirely down to nature but to the energies of the Hunter
Blair family, which has lived in Ayrshire since the 12th century. Sir David
Hunter Blair commissioned both the construction of the neo-Tudor castle and
the diversion of the Girvan as part of a redesign of the landscape in the
early 1800s.
His great great grandson, Jamie Hunter Blair, estate manager, Lloyd's Name,
chairman of the Historic Houses Association in Scotland, vice-chairman of
the Scottish Historic Buildings Trust, former Christie's agent and 'eligible
bachelor', has inherited this 'pile', which is the source of his wealth yet
also threatens to sap it.
Like many of those who still retain their family seat, he feels like one of
an endangered species. 'To keep a place like this, you have to be seriously
rich, and most people are not; which is why these historic houses are going
at such a rate,' says Hunter Blair.
Four of the eight most important historic houses in south Ayrshire are for
sale, he says, and have been on the market for at least a year while their
condition deteriorates. 'The HHA (this month) is publishing a survey of
what's happened in the last three years to all the houses that have been
sold and it's very depressing reading, because once they have been sold, and
fall out of the family's hands, they tend to get sold again and again.'
Hunter Blair's inheritance includes a maintenance fund for Blairquhan castle
and its 500 acres of parkland. The fund was valued at over Pounds 390,000
after the death of his father, Sir James Hunter Blair, in 1985.
'The income is barely enough to keep one gardener going, and so far we've
resisted the temptation to use the capital,' says Hunter Blair, who believes
the government is short-sighted in its policy towards preserving Britain's
historic homes.
Maintenance funds are trust funds dedicated to the benefit of, and repairs
to, a heritage property. Although they are free of inheritance tax, they
attract income and capital gains tax. For several years, the HHA has argued
that they should be exempt from both.
Sir David acquired the original castle and land as a result of his father's
successful Edinburgh banking career and fortuitous marriage. Hunter Blair's
own flirtation with banking was not a success. After taking a degree in
history at Oxford, he went, at his father's suggestion, to what is now Hill
Samuel. After two years, the bank called him in and asked him whether he
really thought his future was in banking.
He then went to learn about estate management on an estate owned by the Duke
of Buccleuch, Britain's largest landowner, and has been involved in managing
the family estate ever since.
Hunter Blair estimates that it costs roughly Pounds 100,000 to keep the
house going every year. The maintenance trust is one way of helping towards
the costs, but the traditional activities of farming, forestry and letting
farms are no longer the solution. Hunter Blair 'lost more money than you
would believe' in farming. 'All that was left was the chance to have income
from visitors,' he says.
The estate has six holiday cottages, which are booked for up to six months
in advance. From such small but encouraging signs, the decision was made to
hire out the castle itself for income. There has been a shift away from
chasing rich Americans towards corporate hospitality, which Hunter Blair has
found to be a more reliable form of income.
Companies which use the house for conferences include Scottish Enterprise,
Caledonian Paper and BPCC, the printing company. Under the terms of the
maintenance fund, the house is open to the public for 25 days a year, but
the amount raised is tiny - only Pounds 2,846 last year - while the income
from hiring out the house last year was Pounds 66,418.
How is the shortfall made up? 'In the past, Lloyd's has been a very great
help in bridging the gap between income and expenditure,' said Hunter Blair,
who has been a Name since 1959. 'In the good old days we were doing very
well.'
Lloyd's provided a reliable and valuable flow of income - Pounds 17,000 in
1971, Pounds 26,000 in 1980 and Pounds 56,000 in 1989. However, Hunter Blair
suffered losses of Pounds 71,000 in 1991 and Pounds 56,000 last year, and he
expects his reserves to be cleared out this year.
He is far from bitter, and has no intention of leaving Lloyd's. 'I'm still
very grateful to Lloyd's, and I believe my agents when they say things are
going to improve. Without Lloyd's this place would have gone,' he said.
The losses have had an impact on his own portfolio, managed by Murray
Johnstone. Three to four years ago, the portfolio stood at Pounds 350,000;
it is now down to Pounds 225,000, of which the Lloyd's deposit element is
Pounds 175,000. Murray Johnstone has put the maximum investment each year
into personal equity plans, which it runs as an integral part of the
portfolio. The Pep portfolio itself stands at Pounds 50,000.
Hunter Blair, who says he has never had much aptitude for, or interest in,
money, has been happy to leave investment decisions to Murray Johnstone. The
only time he intervened was to suggest buying shares in Christie's, the
auction house, for which he used to be the Ayrshire representative for many
years. 'It's the only time I've suggested anything to them. They kept saying
they aren't low enough, but since they've bought them, they've done very
well,' he says.
'The other thing I've got is that my grandmother very kindly left me a big
trust,' says Hunter Blair, who is the life income tenant of the trust, which
is also managed by Murray Johnstone and is worth about Pounds 500,000.
It is invested in blue-chip companies such as General Electric, British
Aerospace, BTR and British Gas. Three or four years ago a small percentage
of the fund was put into the income shares of split-capital investment
trusts, such as Jos Holdings, to meet the need for additional income. Most
of the fund is invested in the UK, though there is a holding in the Pacific
rim through Murray Johnstone's own Scottish Asian fund.
Hunter Blair shared his father's love of art, and the two built up a
collection over 30 years of Scottish colourists, including works by Cadell
and Peploe.
Some of the paintings have increased 100-fold in value. 'They were bought
because we liked them, and the capital appreciation has been an unlooked for
bonus,' says Hunter Blair.
Other investments included a number of with-profits endowment policies from
Equitable Life, which matured two years ago when Hunter Blair was 65 years
old. There are debts: the estate has run up an overdraft over the years of
Pounds 190,000. 'You'll never really get enough for a place like this. But
you just have to keep trying.'
He has some life insurance but no pension to speak of since, as he readily
admits, he does not need one thanks to his grandmother's trust:
'If I didn't have this place, I'd be frightfully well-off, wouldn't I?'
