<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (23): Charges have a
big impact on returns - Research reveals that, over the long term, you
actually pay more in commission if you opt for a series of single premium
payments, rather than a regular-premium plan / How to buy it?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST INVESTORS automatically take a hard look at a provider's performance
record before parting with their cash, but it is now widely recognised that
life office management charges and commission paid to advisers also have a
significant impact on the overall return.
Unfortunately, with most personal pension plans it is not easy to work out
what you are being charged. Much will depend on the way you pay for your
advice and the choice of premium arrangement.
Advisers come in various guises, but the majority still work on a commission
basis whereby they are remunerated by the provider on the sale of a product.
The amount of the commission will depend on the product type, the investment
term, the level of contribution, and whether this is paid on a regular basis
or as a single premium.
Commission rates have gone up by between 30 per cent and 50 per cent since
1989 when the Maximum Commissions Agreement (MCA) was abandoned. The MCA was
an agreement between providers to set a maximum ceiling for commission to
independent advisers, to encourage them to select products on merit rather
than on remuneration.
Since the MCA's demise in 1989, many life offices have also abandoned the
10-year limit on renewal commission and now pay this throughout the entire
term. Renewal commission is relatively modest compared with initial
commission, but nevertheless adds to your total costs.
Regular premiums - whether monthly or annual - make good sense, because they
establish a savings discipline for those with regular earnings. However,
once agreed, the premium level must be adhered to, otherwise you might face
penalties.
Single premiums suit the self-employed or those with erratic earnings who do
not want to lock into a regular payment commitment.
One of the common mistakes investors make is to assume that it is always
'cheaper' to pay single premiums, since these contributions attract a
commission rate of 5.2 per cent. But it is important to remember that this
deduction is made on every premium, whereas the commission costs of regular
plans only appear higher because the bulk of the payment for the entire term
is paid up-front and therefore has a dramatic affect on your early
contributions.
The commission on a regular-premium plan, whether monthly or annual, is
usually paid to the adviser as a lump sum when the sale is made. The
provider then recoups this amount from your premiums during an 'initial'
period of up to 27 months on long-term pension plans. Typically, this can
account for 60 per cent or more of premiums paid during this period; which
is why, if you terminate your plan early, the pot is virtually empty.
However, after the initial period, ongoing costs should be very modest.
Research by Professional Life reveals that, over the long term, you will
actually pay more in commission if you opt for a series of single premium
payments. Take, for example, a Pounds 100 per month or Pounds 1,200 a year
regular-premium plan, and compare it with a series of single premiums of
Pounds 1,200 a year. All result in a total investment of Pounds 48,000 after
40 years.
For the regular-premium method, the total commission after 40 years is
Pounds 2,010, whereas the single-premium route pays total commission of
Pounds 2,496 after this period. As a percentage of your total investment,
the single-premium commission works out at 5.2 per cent, while the
regular-premium commission works out at approximately 4.2 per cent.
So, if you intend to stick with a personal pension plan, don't automatically
assume it is better value to go the single-premium route. However, what you
have to remember about the regular-premium plan is that, for any given term,
you actually pay most of the total commission during the 'initial period',
so your initial deductions are very high.
Jim Roberts, general manager at Professional Life, suggested that investors
should make their decisions in two separate stages:
'First, you need to decide how you want to invest. For example, do you need
the discipline of regular premiums, or would a series of single premiums
suit you better? Only when you have made that decision should you consider
how you are going to pay for the advice and look at how to achieve the best
value.'
For the average investor, Mr Roberts reckons regular monthly premium
arrangements are the safer approach. He explained:
'The important benefit of regular plans is what's known as 'pound cost
averaging'. Since your premiums continue to be invested when unit prices are
low, you benefit from the cheaper costs, and this helps offset the higher
price of units when the stock market is booming. Single-premium payments
must be timed carefully, to avoid the common mistake of only investing when
the stock market is doing well.'
Once you have decided the frequency with which you want to pay your
premiums, you can look at the various ways of paying for your advice. Each
method has its drawbacks and should be discussed in full with your adviser.
Fee-based advice is growing in popularity, because it separates the giving
of advice from the sale of a product. However, fees usually attract a VAT
charge, while commission does not. Also, since commission is deducted from
your premiums, it benefits from the tax relief awarded to all contributions
to approved pension plans. Clearly there is no tax relief on fees. A
minority of providers, like Professional Life, allow the adviser and client
to determine a fee and then deduct this in the form of commission to avoid
the VAT and tax-relief problems.
Some advisers are prepared to rebate part of the commission paid by the
provider. However, these payments can cause tax problems, and many advisers
recommend that their client reinvests the commission they have agreed to
forego, to avoid this complication.
Of course, the commission to the adviser is only one of your costs when you
sign up for a personal pension. Life office charges can be considerable, and
unfortunately in most cases are virtually impossible to assess. Clive
Grimley, senior manager at actuaries and fee based advisers Gissings, said:
'There is a whole range of charges to take into account. For example, the
bid/offer spread which knocks about 5 per cent off your fund. Then there are
'initial', or 'capital', units, which account for the first few years'
premiums and on which higher charges are levied throughout the term of the
policy. On top of that, there are annual management charges, policy charges,
membership charges, fund management charges . . . the list goes on and on.'
So what can the consumer do to avoid the worst excesses of the system? The
most important point is to get expert advice, to help you select a policy
that is good value as well as flexible when it comes to early retirement
without penalty, for example.
Above all, however you plan to pay for your advice, make sure your adviser
is truly independent and has enough expertise to conduct research on all the
top providers. The adviser should be conversant with each provider's
charging structure and should be able to strike up a deal to offset some of
the charges and, where appropriate, to reinvest commission or arrange
non-commission terms.
</TEXT>
