<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (18): At last the
tide is turning for ex-wives - Two legal cases and a government study group
offer new hope for women who face retirement in the wake of a broken
marriage / Divorce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PENSIONS industry, assisted by the legal profession, has come to grips
with what too many divorcees realise only too late: that a pension, too, is
an asset accumulated during a marriage, and that both parties have a claim
on it.
Unfortunately, many wives have found themselves past retirement age with
nothing but minimum state benefits and whatever wealth they were able to
garner from a broken marriage.
There is general agreement that the status quo has been radically unfair to
many homemakers who had relied on their husband's income for support, and
counted on it into retirement.
But because of the ambiguities of the law - and perhaps through failure to
recognise a pension for what it really is - divorce lawyers have rarely
sought to divide pension entitlements when a marriage has come to an end.
Hence the shock-waves earlier this year from a case brought by the widow of
the former Tory MP, Sir Eldon Griffiths, who was left to face old age with
maintenance of just 5p a year. She successfully sued her lawyers for failing
to ensure that her husband's pension entitlement, built up over a 30-year
marriage, was divided between them. The Court agreed with Mrs Griffiths, and
awarded her a one-off Pounds 21,802 payment.
Another sign that the legal tide is turning in favour of ex-wives was
contained in a ruling a few weeks later, in a case identified only as B v B.
In this case, Mr Justice Ewbank, in the High Court, upheld a decision by a
district judge to alter the terms of a husband's pension, to give his former
wife an immediate annuity and a pension.
The case involved a 60-year-old man, who was entitled to receive his
pension, and his 50-year-old wife. The man held a 52 per cent stake in the
company he worked for, and pensions lawyers said the ruling had particular
implications for self-administered schemes in small companies, which may now
have to pay out annuities and pensions to wives when employees become
divorced.
But even if neither B v B nor Mrs Griffiths' settlement prompts a sea-change
in legal opinion, a landmark document on the subject certainly will.
In May, the Pensions Management Institute and the Law Society, after 15
months of laborious deliberation, produced a paper suggesting legal changes
which would confirm that pension entitlement accumulated during a marriage
is indeed jointly owned, just like any other long-term savings or
investment. They suggest four possible ways of dividing pension entitlement
which, among other things, would allow pension fund trustees, for the first
time, to direct payments to someone other than the scheme member.
The division of pension rights after a divorce is also one of 81 questions
under consideration by a government advisory panel on pension reform,
chaired by Professor Roy Goode. Pensions lawyers expect the PMI/Law Society
recommendations to be incorporated into the Goode Committee's final
recommendations.
The report of the PMI and the Law Society offers four possible scenarios for
the division of pension rights following divorce. The advantages of each
would depend on the circumstances of the divorcing couple:
Pension rights might continue undisturbed, but their value be taken into
account. Any reallocation of resources between the couple would be made by
adjustment of non-pension assets.
Pension rights might be 'earmarked', so that they continue undisturbed
during the working spouse's employment, but, once the payment date becomes
effective, a portion of the benefit would be automatically directed to the
other spouse.
Pension benefits might be split within a scheme, so that the scheme member's
rights are reduced by a specified amount and resources from the scheme
released to provide, within the scheme, a package of benefit rights for the
former spouse, as though she or he had been a full scheme member as well.
Through the use of pension transfers, a scheme member's pension rights might
be reduced, and the difference used to provide a transfer value to be
shifted to an alternative scheme on behalf of the former spouse.
The study group recommends the last method as the most attractive, because
it leaves room for a clean-break divorce settlement and imposes relatively
little administrative expense on pension schemes.
The first method is currently in use in Scotland, where the courts have
already come to grips with the concept that pension entitlement accrued
during a marriage is a jointly-held asset. However, there are difficulties
associated with reliance on this method alone.
The solution is only workable where there are sufficient assets other than
pension entitlement. In cases where there are substantial jointly held
savings or investments, for instance, a husband may surrender a portion of
the investment which he is entitled to, in lieu of a wife's agreement to
forego pension benefits of equivalent value.
But when other assets are not available - or where they may be illiquid,
such as a family home in which an ex-wife and dependent children are living
 -this form of pension settlement is less satisfactory.
Of all the pension issues facing the lawmakers, the division of pensions
upon divorce is hardly the thorniest nor the most commercially sensitive.
Yet it is among the areas of greatest concern to one of society's most
vulnerable groups, elderly women.
</TEXT>
<XX>
