<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (12): Japan's royal
wedding fails to rekindle consumer confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THOSE who already hold Japanese stocks, the recent rise in the yen,
coupled with uncertainty over an economic recovery and the political
situation, may pose a strong reason to liquidate.
The Nikkei average, which rose 9.8 per cent during the first quarter of the
year, has stumbled around the 19,500 level since investors became
increasingly wary of the sharp advance during March. Thanks to the strong
performance in April, the leading index of 225 stocks managed to rise 5.4
per cent during the three months to the end of June; however, the 20,000
level has proved difficult to pass.
Strong foreign buying, together with continued help from the government's
public fund purchase operation, supported the index above the 20,000 level
during April, pushing the p/e ratio close to 80. However, the corporate
results season in May revealed that Japanese companies would post a 30 per
cent drop in pre-tax profits for the year ending next March, prompting some
investors to ponder the high valuation figures.
Consumer confidence failed to be spurred, in spite of hopes that the royal
wedding in June between Crown Prince Naruhito and Princess Masako, the
former career diplomat, would trigger a recovery in retail demand as some
economists had predicted. It only produced a slight uptick in sales of the
princess's car, the Toyota Corolla, and pearls, which are favoured by the
Japanese royal family.
Even the yen, which has risen to record levels as US trade negotiators have
tried to talk the currency up on the back of Japan's mounting trade surplus,
threatened to undermine the fragile recovery in the manufacturing sector.
The political upheaval, as reformist groups split away from the ruling
Liberal Democratic party, forcing Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, the prime minister, to
dissolve parliament, and uncertainty over another bribery scandal have given
investors an excuse to remain on the sidelines until the July 18 elections
are over.
While caution over the political situation caused a temporary sell-off of
shares, most analysts reckon the end of the LDP's 38-year rule should not
threaten investors. Geoffrey Barker, an economist at Barings Securities in
Tokyo, says that, although a weak LDP may mean difficulty in making
unpopular but necessary decisions, such as tax reform or liberalisation of
markets under pressure from the US, prospects for economic recovery should
be the dominant factor for stock investors.
For the next three months, investors are unlikely to see much action on the
Tokyo stock market, with the Nikkei index fluctuating amid thin volume, as
institutional investment historically dries up. However, while summers have
been unkind to share prices in recent years, the market is still receiving
underlying help from the government's fund support, which may prevent the
Nikkei from falling below 18,500.
Meanwhile, elsewhere in the Pacific region, the Hong Kong stock market,
which gained 11.1 per cent on the quarter, lost steam towards the end of
June, suffering from a gradual outflow of liquidity.
Andrew Hunt, at Thornton Management, which specialises in Asian funds, says
the market will not experience the performance seen over the past nine
months. Capital inflow from China, which has supported asset prices during
that period, is once again flowing back as China's liquidity is squeezed due
to surging inflation.
The rise in the Malaysian stock market, which advanced a marginal 0.2 per
cent over the past quarter, has slowed as the country's government has
tightened its grip on interest rates. However, there seems to be a case for
remaining bullish over Indonesia, which gained 15.9 per cent and is still
supported by competitive export prices and a steady inflow of capital.
Seoul, which rose 12.3 per cent on the quarter, is also expected to continue
its climb, as sluggish domestic demand suggests that there is still room for
interest rates to fall.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
