<DOCNO>FT933-13845</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DGPB4AG8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930716
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (8): The search is
on for recovery stocks - Although many analysts are already upgrading their
earnings forecasts for this year in both the US and the UK, the hard
evidence for this has yet to come through
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS MADE money in the second quarter, based on the FT-Actuaries World
Index. But stock and sector selection was critical, and overall the
important Wall Street and London markets just about marked time, with total
investment returns even under-performing money market rates.
The World Index overall gave sterling-based investors a 6.7 per cent return,
against 9.7 per cent in the first quarter of the year.
Japan again compensated for some poor performances elsewhere, notably in
Europe where France and Germany ended the quarter in negative territory.
Tokyo produced a total return of 19 per cent in sterling terms, following a
January-March positive outcome of 19.5 per cent. Part of this gain was in
the currency, and Japan has yet to get back to the heady days of 1991. But
fund managers late into Tokyo have done very nicely.
The second quarter showed that country selection can be a funny old
business. Italy has been rocked by political scandals, and some big-name
companies, such as Ferruzzi, are in trouble. Yet the Italian market for
local investors rose by a fifth, and higher still in sterling terms. The
uncertain investment rationale there would appear to be that things can only
get better.
Some other markets, which had performed well towards the end of 1992 and in
the first quarter of this year, had setbacks, notably Mexico, Spain and
Australia; but Switzerland, with a close-on 6 per cent return for sterling
investors in the first quarter, pushed ahead to yield almost 50 per cent
better in the April-June period, the solid Swiss franc taking over the
secure European currency role from the D-Mark. Austria, another semi-hedge
against a weakening German currency, managed a return of around 4 per cent.
All of the geographical regions that make up the World Index ended the
quarter in positive territory. The Pacific area overall produced a return of
almost 18 per cent, though less than half that if Japan is excluded. Hong
Kong had another heady quarter, but in often volatile trading, the market
consensus being that the colony and China will somehow work out an amicable
post-1997 arrangement. But in the meantime there are bound to be major
investment scares.
Geographical section was important for fund managers in the second quarter,
but sector-picking was even more important. Investors sensed some economic
recovery in the US and Britain and a bottoming out in Japan, but continental
Europe is still faltering. Low world interest rates are driving more money
into equities, especially in the US where a growing number of mutual funds
are looking at investment opportunities outside their domestic market, and
increasingly at index-tracker instruments.
The search is now on for recovery stocks, rather than secure
recession-proofed holdings. Cyclical stocks are in demand, although not as
yet in the consumer area where spending remains erratic.
The World Index consumer goods and services sector showed a return of less
than 2 per cent in the quarter; but banks and other financial institutions
were some 17 per cent ahead, while electronics and heavy engineering had
returns at or near the mid-teens. Utilities came in at about 7 per cent; the
retail sector had a negative return compared with some 3.5 per cent last
time.
And what is the outlook for the remainder of this year? Most fund managers
are sitting on tidy profits and will want to nurture them. The problem is
that there is no real return to be made on the money markets, unless they
take a punt on currencies, and US long bond yields are at or near historic
lows.
Everyone is looking for recovery stocks, particularly in the medium-size
corporate sector, and selecting successfully there requires a lot of local
market knowledge. No doubt the third quarter will produce Italian-style
performances, but the major markets may well be in sideways mode, although
many analysts are already upgrading their earnings forecasts for this year
in both the US and the UK. The hard evidence for this has yet to come
through.
</TEXT>
