<PROFILE>_AN-DGPB4AG4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930716
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (5): Nine selections
from a global field of 1,400 - Two of this quarter's advisers see growth
potential in the Pacific, and two pick Perpetual funds for total return /
The experts' panel, Unit Trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIT TRUSTS are often cited as an easy way for investors to own shares - but
where does the beginner start? There are over 1,400 trusts to choose from.
So we asked advisers to choose three unit trusts - one for income, one for
capital growth and one for total return. They had complete freedom as to
whether they opted for UK or overseas stock markets.
Graeme Farquharson, of Hill Martin (Asset Management), says: 'Our approach
to unit trust selection is 'top down'. We look at the providers first. How
big are they? How long have they been managing funds? What is their overall
performance? Only when it has satisfied our criteria does a management house
go on our selected list.
'When we examine individual funds, we look at a number of factors in
addition to performance: size, charging structure, the record of the
indiviual manager, the investment philosophy. When performance is analysed,
it should be on a offer-to-bid basis, and should be based on consistency
over at least five years.
'Using the above criteria, my recommendations are:
GROWTH: the Govett Pacific Strategy fund. 'We believe that the geographic
area most likely to produce above-average growth in the medium to long term
is the Far East, and we have selected a fund which can include investments
in Japan.
'The Pacific Strategy fund was formed in 1987 and has been managed for the
past three years by Peter Robson. The investment policy is 'top down', in
that the asset allocation is decided first, based on information received
from Govett's Singapore office, together with views gathered from brokers
worldwide and its own research department.
'Performance has been splendid, the fund having produced just short of 140
per cent for the five years to January 1, 1993, and just under 40 per cent
for one year to the same date.
TOTAL RETURN: Buckmaster Income. 'While the Buckmaster Income fund is
categorised as an income fund, its yield is relatively low at 4.25 per cent.
This allows for both future income growth and a very real prospect of
underlying capital growth. The fund has been managed for the past 3 1/2
years by Tim Gregory.
'The investment policy is 'top down', in that the macro strategy for a
rolling five years is first agreed. Income funds have had considerable
difficulty maintaining a high yield, due to the trend of dividend cuts and
the effects of the recent changes in Advance Corporation Tax. This fund,
however, achieves its core income from convertible preference shares, and is
then free to make investments in lower-income, good-quality stocks.
'Performance has been good, with returns being 81 per cent for the five
years to January 1, 1993 and 21.6 per cent for one year to the same date.
INCOME: Perpetual High Income fund. 'Perpetual has built up a quite
remarkable investment performance and won numerous industry awards. The High
Income fund was formed in 1988, and is managed by Neil Woodford. It is
invested to achieve a high income from a spread of international securities,
with at least 50 per cent in the UK or EC. The current estimated gross yield
is 5.13 per cent per annum.
Past performance has been impressive, with growth of 38.5 per cent for the
three years to January 1993.'
Peter Tonkin, investment director of Towry Law, chooses:
INCOME: GT Smaller Companies Dividend fund. 'In searching for a recommended
income unit trust, I decided on an equity income fund, because of my wish to
see a growing income. I choose a fund investing in UK companies, because the
yields available are more attractive than those from most other markets.
'GT Smaller Companies Dividend fund, managed by Doug Hunter, was launched in
September 1989, and is one of a handful of unit trusts seeking an
above-average level of income from a portfolio of shares of smaller UK
companies.
'The main investment theme of the fund is to choose companies which have
good, solid businesses and sound managements but which are currently ignored
by the stock market. These companies must have the potential, over the
medium term, to grow their dividends, so that the fund can deliver income
growth to investors.
'In June, the gross yield was just over 6 per cent - about 50 per cent
higher than the average yield from UK equities.
GROWTH: Schroder UK Enterprise Fund. 'I stay with the UK market in my
selection of a growth fund. Looking ahead to further recovery in the
economy, I pass over funds investing in our larger (and therefore more
defensive) companies, searching instead for a fund which will move swiftly
into those companies that are going to show above-average growth, and
hopefully above-average share price rises, as economic conditions change.
'The Schroder UK Enterprise Fund, managed by Jim Cox, is my choice here. It
is primarily a stock-picking fund.
It has had an excellent performance since launch in August 1988, by focusing
the portfolio on 40-45 stocks.
TOTAL RETURN: Perpetual Global Bond fund. 'Now is the time for me to
recommend exposure to overseas economies (and currencies) through bonds or
fixed-interest investments via the Perpetual Global Bond fund. Perpetual
appointed Alpha Global Fixed Income Managers as advisers to their fund. In
June, the quoted gross yield was just under 6 1/2 per cent and the total
return since launch in April 1992 had been more than 25 per cent - making it
the top-performing fund in its sector over that period.'
John Edwards, consultant, Berry Birch &amp; Noble, says:
'Recommending individual unit trusts is a mug's game. As the statutory
warning says: past performance is not necessarily a guide to the future.
Yesterday's winner often turns out to be tomorrow's loser. Unfortunately the
contrarian theory, that poorly performing funds stand the best chance of
moving to the top of the table, is not proven. Some unit trusts consistently
lose value year after year.
'However, there are various basic criteria to be considered. First, there is
the risk/reward ratio. Can the investor afford to lose in hopes of a big
gain, or would he prefer something a bit safer with less potential reward?
'Unit trusts are essentially long-term investments, partly because it takes
time to recoup dealing charges. But it depends on what is meant by
long-term. It is no good simply selecting unit trusts or sectors which are
currently flavour of the month. Things can change pretty quickly, and it is
easy to ramp up short-term performance. For the long-term investor, it is
important to take into account the record and pedigree of the companies
offering unit trusts.
'For example, banks over the years have a dismal performance record, with
few exceptions. Insurance companies may have other fish to fry, and not be
too concerned about their unit trusts.
'So there is a case for picking unit trusts run by independently-owned
investment houses with a long-term record.
INCOME: Fidelity High Income. 'A few years ago, it would have been
unthinkable not automatically to include M&amp;G and Fidelity in any list of
unit trust recommendations. However, both groups have suffered considerable
setbacks in their performance in the last few years, although they appear to
have been recovering ground more recently.
'In fact, if income is required the recently launched Fidelity High Income
trust is not a bad choice. It invests in a mixture of equities and
fixed-interest securities. This helps to provide an above-average yield,
stability in the event of a stock market crash, and the prospect of limited
capital growth. It is an ideal vehicle for Pep investors wanting tax-free
income.
'Newton Income has had a tremendous performance over the past five years.
But there must be doubts as to whether this can be maintained following its
transition from a small to large fund as the result of a big inflow of
money.
GROWTH: Schroder Pacific Growth. 'For capital growth, the best prospects for
long-term capital growth appear to be offered by the Pacific Basin and Far
East markets, including China but excluding Japan. Schroder has always been
strong in that area, and its Pacific Growth fund has a consistently good
record.
TOTAL RETURN: Perpetual High Income. 'No one looking at unit trusts can
ignore the all-round performance achieved by Perpetual in recent years. It
has a cluster of top-performing trusts in several sectors. One could almost
choose any of their funds. For total return, I would favour the Perpetual
High Income fund, which not only has a reasonable yield but also a good
growth record.'
</TEXT>
