<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Drug shares decline on
downgrade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A LATE burst of buying allowed US stock markets to recover from early losses
and big declines in drug issues and finish the day little changed and still
close to record highs, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 8.38 at 3,550.93,
within four points of the all-time high set in late May. The more broadly
based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended just 0.86 softer at 449.22, although the
Nasdaq composite was down 3.80 at 708.69 after the previous day's record
peak. Trading volume on the New York SE was 278m shares.
Following Wednesday's gains, when stocks neared, or broke through, record
highs, market observers were not surprised when prices fell from the start
amid some early profit-taking. It was not until the last hour of trading
that prices rallied from their lows amid late buying. The day's economic
news was mixed: a smaller than expected rise in weekly jobless claims and a
sharp drop in the Philadelphia Federal Reserve's July index of local
business activity.
Although corporate earnings came in quickly, the day's main story was the
drugs sector. Prices tumbled in busy trading after Ms Christina Heuer, the
sector analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham, downgraded her investment
rating on the pharmaceuticals group as a whole from 'neutral' to
'underperform'.
Ms Heuer said she believed that some of the big drug companies will cut
their dividends to preserve cash, and that equity prices could fall by a
further 20 to 30 per cent in the short term.
Almost every major drug stock fell sharply on the downgrade. Pfizer shed
Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 63 1/4 , Merck Dollars 1 to Dollars 33 3/4 ,
Schering-Plough Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 66 1/8 , American Home Products
Dollars 1 to Dollars 63 5/8 , Bristol-Myers Squibb Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars
58, Warner-Lambert Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 67 1/2 and Eli Lilly Dollars
7/8 to Dollars 46 3/4 .
Another stock to be hit by a downgrade, and disappointing second-quarter
results, was Storage Technology, which plummeted Dollars 7 7/8 to Dollars 33
1/4 after Lehman Brothers and Kemper Securities lowered their ratings on the
stock and cut 1993 earnings forecasts.
Time Warner dipped Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 38 1/8 after posting a
second-quarter loss, although underlying operating earnings were up by 10
per cent.
On the Nasdaq market, Scitex plunged Dollars 9 5/8 to Dollars 28 3/8 on a
profits warning, and SynOptics Communications slid Dollars 6 1/4 to Dollars
31 3/4 on disappointing second-quarter earnings.
Canada
TORONTO ended on a mildly easier note after heavy trading. The TSE 300 index
lost 10.4 at 3,931.3 and declining issues outscored rises by 397 to 328.
Volume amounted to 65m shares valued at CDollars 732m.
Eight of the 14 sub-group indices were lower, with mining down 1.7 per cent
and leading the way.
American Barrick, CDollars  1/8 up at CDollars 31 1/8 , reported sharply
higher second-quarter and six-month earnings and revenues.
